I"»}<hr />

<h2 id="strategic-game">Strategic game</h2>

<p>A strategic game (with ordinal preferences) consists of</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>a set of players</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>for each player, a set of actions</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>for each player, preferences over the set of action profiles</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>Very general model-no specific economic structure.</p>

<hr />
<p>Examples:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>firms competing for business</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>political candidates competing for votes</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>jury members deciding on a verdict</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>animals fighting over prey</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>bidders competing in an auction</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>the evolution of siblings‚Äô behavior towards each other - competing experts‚Äô incentives to provide correct diagnoses</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>legislators‚Äô voting behavior under pressure from interest groups</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>the role of threats and punishment in long-term relationships.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p>Notes on elements:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>A player may be an individual human being, or any other decisionmaking entity like a government, a board of directors, the leadership of a revolutionary movement, or even a flower or an animal.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>There are no restrictions on the set of actions available to a player: may, for example, be a huge set containing complicated plans that cover a variety of contingencies.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Can represent preferences by payoff function.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Terminology: <strong>Action profile</strong> $=$ list of actions, one for each player</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />
<h2 id="example-prisoners-dilemma">Example: Prisoner‚Äôs Dilemma</h2>

<p>Strategic game:</p>

<p><strong>Players</strong> The two suspects.</p>

<p><strong>Actions</strong> Each player‚Äôs set of actions is {Quiet, Fink }.</p>

<p><strong>Preferences</strong> Suspect 1 ‚Äòs ordering of the action profiles, from best to worst, is (Fink, Quiet) (she finks and suspect 2 remains quiet, so she is freed), (Quiet, Quiet) (she gets one year in prison), (Fink, Fink) (she gets three years in prison), (Quiet, Fink) (she gets four years in prison). Suspect 2‚Äôs ordering is (Quiet, Fink), (Quiet, Quiet), (Fink, Fink), (Fink, Quiet).</p>

<hr />

<p>Choose payoff functions that represent preferences.</p>

\[\def\arraystretch{1.5}
\begin{array}{|c| c |c|}
\hline&amp; \text{Quiet}  (C)&amp; \text{Fink} (D)\\
\hline \text{ Quiet } (C) &amp; 2,2 &amp; 0,3 \\
\hline \text{ Fink }(D) &amp; 3,0 &amp; 1,1 \\
\hline
\end{array}\]

<p>Game models other situations: e.g. arms race, duopoly.</p>

<p><strong>Important point</strong>: game is defined by players‚Äô <em>preferences</em> (how they rank action profiles), not their <em>payoffs</em>. Hence, any game with different numbers but the same ranking over action profiles is also a prisoners‚Äô dilemma.</p>

<hr />
<h2 id="example-battle-of-sexes-bos">Example: Battle of Sexes (BoS)</h2>

<p>In the Prisoner‚Äôs dilemma the players agree that $(C, C)$ is a desirable outcome, though each has an incentive to deviate from this outcome.</p>

<p>In BoS the players disagree about the outcome that is desirable.</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Two people wish to go out together to a concert of music by either Bach or Stravinsky.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Their main concern is to go out together, but one person prefers Bach and the other person prefers Stravinsky.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>If they go to different concerts then each of them is equally unhappy listening to the music of either composer.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p>Choosing payoff representations, game is: 
\(\def\arraystretch{1.5}
\begin{array}{|r|c|c|} 
\hline&amp; \text { Bach } &amp; \text { Stravinsky } \\
\hline\text { Bach } &amp; 2,1 &amp; 0,0 \\
\hline\text { Stravinsky } &amp; 0,0 &amp; 1,2 \\
\hline
\end{array}\)</p>

<p><strong>Other interpretations</strong>:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Two officials of a political party announcing a policy (better off if they announce same one).</li>
  <li>Merging firms that currently use different computer systems and need to choose the one to use after merging.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2 id="example-guessing-two-thirds-of-the-average">Example: Guessing two-thirds of the average</h2>

<p>Game with <em>three</em> players where each player chooses a number between $1$ and $10$. One with number closest to $\frac{2}{3}$ of the average wins.</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Players</strong>: Three players</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Actions</strong>: $1,\ldots,10$</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Payoffs</strong>: Set $A=\frac{1}{3}(a_1+a_2+a_3)$ (the average). Player $i$ <em>wins</em> if
\(\left|a_{i}-\frac{2}{3}A\right|\leq \left|a_{j}-\frac{2}{3}A\right|\) 
for all $j\neq i$. Let $n$ be the number of winners. Then each winner receives $1/n$.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2 id="example-cournots-oligopoly-game">Example: Cournot‚Äôs oligopoly game</h2>

<p>Game with two players, where each player chooses an action from a continuum.</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Players:</strong> firms</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Actions of each firm</strong>: set of outputs</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Preferences of each firm</strong>: represented by payoff function $u_{i}$ with
  \(u_{i}\left(q_{1}, \ldots, q_{n}\right)=q_{i} P\left(q_{1}+\cdots+q_{n}\right)-C_{i}\left(q_{i}\right)\)
  Can‚Äôt be represented in table: more than 2 players, and continuum of actions for each player.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />
<h2 id="nash-equilibrium">Nash equilibrium</h2>

<p>What actions will players take?</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Assume that each player acts rationally: chooses best action.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>But best action depends on other players‚Äô actions. So a player must form a belief about the other players‚Äô actions.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>Belief could come from introspection about what you would do in the other person‚Äôs shoes. But that‚Äôs NOT the approach used here (and leads to an infinite regress ‚Ä¶ ).</p>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>How are beliefs formed? Based on experience. 
  Experienced players $\Rightarrow$ correct beliefs.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>But players don‚Äôt interact repeatedly with the same opponents. Rather: random matching. [Think of walking along the street, meeting random people head-on and having to decide whether to step to the left or to the right.]</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>So: (a) each player chooses best action for her, given her beliefs about the other players‚Äô actions, and $(b)$ each player‚Äôs beliefs are correct.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>A Nash equilibrium is an action profile $a^{<em>}$ with the property that no player $i$ can do better by choosing an action different from $a_{i}^{</em>}$, given that every other player $j$ adheres to $a_{j}^{*}$.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>In idealized setting in which the players in any given play of the game are drawn randomly from a collection of populations, a Nash equilibrium corresponds to a steady state.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Nash equilibrium is alternatively stable ‚Äúsocial norm‚Äù.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The second component of the theory of Nash equilibrium-that the players‚Äô beliefs about each other‚Äôs actions are correct</li>
      <li>implies, in particular, that two players‚Äô beliefs about a third player‚Äôs action are the same. For this reason, the condition is sometimes referred to as the requirement that the players‚Äù ‚Äúexpectations are coordinated‚Äù.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>In applications, often idealized setting doesn‚Äôt fit! For example, in some cases the players do not have much experience with the game; in others they do not view each play of the game in isolation.</li>
  <li>Whether the notion of Nash equilibrium is appropriate in any given situation is a matter of judgment. In some cases, a poor fit with the idealized setting may be mitigated by other considerations.</li>
  <li>For example, inexperienced players may be able to draw conclusions about their opponents‚Äô likely actions from their experience in other situations, or from other sources. Ultimately, the test of the appropriateness of the notion of Nash equilibrium is whether it gives us insights into the problem at hand.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p><strong>DEFINITION</strong></p>

<p>The action profile $a^{<em>}$ in a strategic game with ordinal preferences is a Nash equilibrium if, for every player $i$ and every action $a_{i}$ of player $i, a^{</em>}$ is at least as good according to player $i^{\prime}$ s preferences as the action profile $\left(a_{i}, a_{-i}^{<em>}\right)$ in which player $i$ chooses $a_{i}$ while every other player $j$ chooses $a_{i}^{</em>}$. Equivalently, for every player $i$ 
\(u_{i}\left(a^{*}\right) \geq u_{i}\left(a_{i}, a_{-i}^{*}\right)\)
 for every action $a_{i}$ of player $i$ where $u_{i}$ is a payoff function that represents player $i^{\prime}$ s preferences.</p>

<hr />
<h2 id="examples">Examples</h2>
<p><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br />
Prisoner‚Äôs Dilemma, BoS,  Matching Pennies</p>

<hr />

<p><strong>Stag Hunt</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>A sentence in Discourse on the origin and foundations of inequality among men (1755) by the philosopher Jean-Jacques Rousseau discusses group of hunters who wish to catch a stag.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>They succeed if they all remain sufficiently attentive, but each is tempted to desert her post and catch a hare.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Model: Each of a group of hunters has two options: she may remain attentive to the pursuit of a stag, or she may catch a hare. If all hunters pursue the stag, they catch it and share it equally; if any hunter devotes her energy to catching a hare, the stag escapes, and the hare belongs to the defecting hunter alone. Each hunter prefers a share of the stag to a hare. The strategic game that corresponds to this specification is:</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p><strong>Players</strong> The hunters. (Note: Many players.)</p>

<p><strong>Actions</strong> Each player‚Äôs set of actions is ${$ Stag, Hare $}$.</p>

<p><strong>Preferences</strong> For each player, the action profile in which all players choose Stag (resulting in her obtaining a share of the stag) is ranked highest, followed by any profile in which she chooses Hare (resulting in her obtaining a hare), followed by any profile in which she chooses Stag and one or more of the other players chooses Hare (resulting in her leaving empty-handed).</p>

<p>Like other games with many players, this game cannot easily be presented in a table like that in Figure $1 .$ For the case in which there are two hunters, the game is as follows:</p>

<hr />

\[\def\arraystretch{1.5}
\begin{array}{|c|c|c|} 
\hline&amp;\text { Stag } &amp;\text { Hare } \\
\hline\text { Stag } &amp; 2,2 &amp; 0,1 \\
\hline\text { Hare } &amp; 1,0 &amp; 1,1 \\
\hline
\end{array}\]

<hr />

<p><strong>Nash equilibrium</strong>:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Inspection shows that the two-player Stag Hunt has two Nash equilibria: (Stag, Stag) and (Hare,Hare).</p>
  </li>
  <li>Unlike the Nash equilibria of BoS, one of these equilibria is better for both players than the other: each player prefers (Stag, Stag) to (Hare, Hare).</li>
  <li>This fact has no bearing on the equilibrium status of (Hare, Hare), since the condition for an equilibrium is that a single player cannot gain by deviating, given the other player‚Äôs behavior.</li>
  <li>Put differently, an equilibrium is immune to any unilateral deviation; coordinated deviations by groups of players are not contemplated.</li>
  <li>However, the existence of two equilibria raises the possibility that one equilibrium might more likely be the outcome of the game than the other.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p><strong>First nontrivial argument</strong>:</p>

<p>I argue that the many-player Stag Hunt also has two Nash equilibria: the action profile $($ Stag,$\ldots$, Stag $)$ in which every player joins in the pursuit of the stag, and the profile (Hare,‚Ä¶, Hare) in which every player catches a hare.</p>

<ul>
  <li>$($ Stag,$\ldots$, Stag $)$ is a Nash equilibrium because each player prefers this profile to that in which she alone chooses Hare.</li>
  <li>(Hare, ‚Ä¶, Hare) is a Nash equilibrium because each player prefers this profile to that in which she alone pursues the stag.</li>
  <li>No other profile is a Nash equilibrium, because in any other profile at least one player chooses Stag and at least one player chooses Hare, so that any player choosing Stag is better off switching to Hare.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2 id="best-response-functions">Best response functions</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Best response function:</li>
</ul>

\[B_{i}\left(a_{-i}\right)=\left\{a_{i} \text { in } A_{i}: u_{i}\left(a_{i}, a_{-i}\right) \geq u_{i}\left(a_{i}^{\prime}, a_{-i}\right) \text { for all } a_{i}^{\prime} \text { in } A_{i}\right\}\]

<hr />

<p><strong>Examples</strong> 
<br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> 
Prisoner‚Äôs Dilemma, BoS, Stag hunt</p>

<hr />

<p>\(\begin{array}{c|c|c|c|} 
&amp; L &amp; C &amp; R \\
\hline  T &amp; 1,2^{*} &amp; 2^{*}, 1 &amp; 1^{*}, 0 \\
\hline  M &amp; 2^{*}, 1^{*} &amp; 0,1^{*} &amp; 0,0 \\
\hline  B &amp; 0,1 &amp; 0,0 &amp; 1^{*}, 2^{*} \\
\hline 
\end{array}\)
<br /> <br /> 
\(B_{1}(L)=\{M\}, B_{1}(R)=\{T, B\} .\)</p>

<hr />

<h3 id="example-guessing-2--3-of-average">Example: Guessing $2 / 3$ of average</h3>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Q: What is best response to $(10,1)$ ?</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>A: $B_{1}(10,1)={2,3,4,5,6}$</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>If others choose 10 and 1, outcomes:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>$1$: tie</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>$2$: $10+1+2=13, \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{13}{3}=\frac{26}{9}=2 \frac{8}{9}$, so wins</p>
      </li>
      <li>$3$: $10+1+3=14, \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{14}{3}=\frac{28}{9}=3 \frac{1}{9}$, so wins</li>
      <li>
        <p>‚Ä¶</p>
      </li>
      <li>$7$: tie between $1$ and $7$</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Set-valued in general; examples where it is singleton.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h3 id="best-responses-and-nash-equilibria">Best responses and Nash equilibria</h3>
<p><br /></p>

<ul>
  <li>Result: $a^{*}$ is a Nash equilibrium if and only if</li>
</ul>

\[a_{i}^{*} \text { is in } B_{i}\left(a_{-i}^{*}\right) \text { for every player } i \text {. }\]

<ul>
  <li>If $B_{i}$ is singleton-valued,</li>
</ul>

\[a_{i}^{*}=b_{i}\left(a_{-i}^{*}\right) \text { for every player } i\]

<ul>
  <li>Write out explicitly for two players:</li>
</ul>

\[\begin{aligned}
&amp;a_{1}^{*}=b_{1}\left(a_{2}^{*}\right) \\
&amp;a_{2}^{*}=b_{2}\left(a_{1}^{*}\right) .
\end{aligned}\]

<hr />

<p>Finding Nash equilibria using best response functions:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Find best response functions</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Find action profiles that satisfy conditions</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p><strong>Example</strong>: Consider the game from earlier
<br /></p>

\[\begin{array}{c|c|c|c|} 
&amp; L &amp; C &amp; R \\
\hline  T &amp; 1,2^{*} &amp; 2^{*}, 1 &amp; 1^{*}, 0 \\
\hline  M &amp; 2^{*}, 1^{*} &amp; 0,1^{*} &amp; 0,0 \\
\hline  B &amp; 0,1 &amp; 0,0 &amp; 1^{*}, 2^{*} \\
\hline 
\end{array}\]

<hr />

<p><img src="https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/9f92a3071f00e68875165b31927b9e09-02.jpg?height=292&amp;width=297&amp;top_left_y=582&amp;top_left_x=498" alt="bg w:10cm left" /></p>

<p>Figure 1. The players‚Äô best response functions for the game above. Player 1 ‚Äòs best responses are indicated by circles, and player 2‚Äôs by dots. The action pairs for which there is both a circle and a dot are the Nash equilibria.</p>

<hr />

<h3 id="example-synergistic-relationship">Example: Synergistic relationship:</h3>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Players: two people</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Actions: Set of nonnegative numbers for each player</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Preferences: represented by payoff function $a_{i}\left(c+a_{j}-a_{i}\right)$.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p>Find best response functions $\left(b_{i}\left(a_{j}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(c+a_{j}\right)\right)$ : see Figure 2 .</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Then solve for Nash equilibrium $((c, c))$.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <h2 id="general-best-responses-not-necessarily-single-valued">‚ÄúGeneral‚Äù best responses (not necessarily single-valued):</h2>
    <p><img src="https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/9f92a3071f00e68875165b31927b9e09-03.jpg?height=404&amp;width=404&amp;top_left_y=218&amp;top_left_x=430" alt="bg w:15cm left" /></p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>Figure 2. The players‚Äô best response functions for the game in the synergistic game. The game has a unique Nash equilibrium, $\left(a_{1}^{<em>}, a_{2}^{</em>}\right)=(c, c)$.</p>

<hr />

<p><img src="https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/9f92a3071f00e68875165b31927b9e09-03.jpg?height=413&amp;width=415&amp;top_left_y=699&amp;top_left_x=430" alt="bg w:15cm left" /></p>

<p>Figure 3. An example of the best response functions of a two-player game in which each player‚Äôs set of actions is an interval of numbers. The set of Nash equilibria of the game consists of the pairs of actions $\left(a_{1}^{<em>}, a_{2}^{</em>}\right)$ and $\left(a_{1}^{* * <em>}, a_{2}^{</em> * <em>}\right)$, and all the pairs of actions on player 2 ‚Äòs best response function between $\left(a_{1}^{</em> <em>}, a_{2}^{</em> <em>}\right)$ and $\left(a_{1}^{</em> * <em>}, a_{2}^{</em> * *}\right)$</p>

<hr />
<h2 id="contributing-to-a-public-good">Contributing to a public good</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>$n$ people</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>each can contribute or not to public good</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>best outcome for $i:$ good is provided and $i$ does not contribute, then good is not provided and $i$ does not contribute, then good is not provided and $i$ contributes</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Nash equilibrium: any $k$ contribute or no one contributes</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p>We now study a model in which TWO people decide not only whether to contribute, but also how much to contribute. More contributions $\Rightarrow$ more of good is provided.</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Person i‚Äôs wealth: $w_{i} .$ Amount she contributes to public good: $c_{i}$ $\left(0 \leq c_{i} \leq w_{i}\right)$. (She spends her remaining wealth $w_{i}-c_{i}$ on ‚Äúprivate goods $^{\prime \prime} .$.)</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Amount of public good $=$ sum of contributions. Each person cares both about the amount of the public good and her consumption of private goods.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Person $i^{\prime}$ s preferences represented by $v_{i}\left(c_{1}+c_{2}\right)+w_{i}-c_{i}\left(c_{1}+c_{2}=\right.$ amount of public good; $w_{i}-c_{i}=$ amount of private good; $v_{i}$ is a funtion!). Function is quasi-linear.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Because $w_{i}$ is a constant, person $i$ ‚Äòs preferences are alternatively represented by the payoff function [leave on board, for later use]</p>
  </li>
</ul>

\[u_{i}\left(c_{1}, c_{2}\right)=v_{i}\left(c_{1}+c_{2}\right)-c_{i}\]

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>This situation is modeled by the following strategic game.</li>
</ul>

<p>Players The two people.</p>

<p>Actions Player i‚Äôs set of actions is the set of her possible contributions (nonnegative numbers less than or equal to $\left.w_{i}\right)$, for $i=1,2$.</p>

<p>Preferences Player i‚Äôs preferences are represented by the payoff function $u_{i}$ given in (1), for $i=1,2$.</p>

<ul>
  <li>Nash equilibrium: Player $1^{\prime} \mathrm{s}$ best response to the contribution $c_{2}$ of player 2 is the value of $c_{1}$ that maximizes $v_{1}\left(c_{1}+c_{2}\right)-c_{1} .$ Without specifying the form of the function $v_{1}$ we cannot explicitly calculate this optimal value. However, we can determine how it varies with $c_{2}$.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Book finds equilibria using elementary means. Probably easier with calculus: - Player 1‚Äôs payoff is $v_{1}\left(c_{1}+c_{2}\right)-c_{1}$.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Fix $c_{2}$. Then $b_{1}\left(c_{2}\right)$ solves</p>
  </li>
</ul>

\[\max _{c_{1}}\left[v_{1}\left(c_{1}+c_{2}\right)-c_{1}\right]\]

<ul>
  <li>Suppose payoff function is concave in $c_{1}$, with an interior maximum. Then look at FOC:</li>
</ul>

\[v_{1}^{\prime}\left(b_{1}\left(c_{2}\right)+c_{2}\right)-1=0\]

<hr />

<p>That means that $b_{1}\left(c_{2}\right)+c_{2}$ is constant, independent of $c_{2} !$ Thus</p>

\[b_{1}\left(c_{2}\right)=K-c_{2}\]

<p>for some $K$, where $b_{1}(0)=K$.</p>

<p>Draw the function $b_{1} .$ See Figure 4 .</p>

<ul>
  <li>$v_{2}$ may be different from $v_{1}$, so $b_{1}(0) \neq b_{2}(0) .$ But both best response functions have same slope of $-1$ (shown in Figure 4 for $\left.b_{1}(0)&gt;b_{2}(0)\right)$.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>SO: if $b_{1}(0)&gt;b_{2}(0)$, game has unique Nash equilibrium, $\left(b_{1}(0), 0\right)$ and if $b_{1}(0)&lt;b_{2}(0)$, unique Nash equilibrium $\left(0, b_{2}(0)\right)$. That is, the person who contributes more when the other person contributes nothing is the only one to make a contribution in a Nash equilibrium. Only if $b_{1}(0)=b_{2}(0)$, which is not likely if the functions $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$ differ, is there an equilibrium in which both people contribute. In this case the downward-sloping parts of the best response functions coincide, so that any pair of contributions $\left(c_{1}, c_{2}\right)$ with $c_{1}+c_{2}=b_{1}(0)$ and $c_{i} \geq 0$ for $i=1,2$ is a Nash equilibrium.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>Summary: Nash equilibrium predicts that, except in unusual circumstances, only one person contributes to the provision of the public good when each person‚Äôs payoff function takes the form $v_{i}\left(c_{1}+c_{2}\right)+$ $w_{i}-c_{i}$, each function $v_{i}\left(c_{i}\right)-c_{i}$ increases to a maximum, then decreases, and each person optimally contributes less than her entire wealth when the other person does not contribute. The person who contributes is the one who wishes to contribute more when the other person does not contribute. In particular, the identity of the person who contributes does not depend on the distribution of wealth; any distribution in which each person optimally contributes less than her entire wealth when the other person does not contribute leads to the same outcome.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p><img src="https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/9f92a3071f00e68875165b31927b9e09-06.jpg?height=308&amp;width=369&amp;top_left_y=219&amp;top_left_x=444" alt="bg left w:10cm" /></p>

<p>Figure 4 . The best response functions for the game of contributing to a public good in a case in which $b_{1}(0)&gt;b_{2}(0)$. The best response function of player 1 is the black line; that of player 2 is the gray line.</p>

<p>End of first half (1h15-1h20)</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="strict-domination">Strict domination</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Prisoner‚Äôs Dilemma.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>A player‚Äôs action ‚Äústrictly dominates‚Äù another action if it is superior, no matter what the other players do:</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>In a strategic game with ordinal preferences, player $i$ ‚Äòs action $a_{i}^{\prime \prime}$ strictly dominates her action $a_{i}^{\prime}$ if</p>

<p>$u_{i}\left(a_{i}^{\prime \prime}, a_{-i}\right)&gt;u_{i}\left(a_{i}^{\prime}, a_{-i}\right)$ for every list $a_{-i}$ of the other players‚Äô actions,</p>

<p>where $u_{i}$ is a payoff function that represents player i‚Äôs preferences. We say that the action $a_{i}^{\prime}$ is strictly dominated.</p>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>E.g. Prisoner‚Äôs Dilemma.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>a strictly dominated action is not used in any Nash equilibrium</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Hence can remove strictly dominated actions iteratively. Example:</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>First eliminate $T$ for player 1, then $C$ for player 2, then $B$ for player 1, then $L$ for player 2. [Note C, e.g., is not strictly dominated in original game.] Figure 5 .</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>NOTE: in guessing $2 / 3$ of the average game actions are not iteratively dominated by pure strategies, so can‚Äôt use this example now.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Note that if $a$ strictly dominates $b, a$ may itself be strictly dominated.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />
<h2 id="weak-domination">Weak domination</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Give simple example with two actions</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Weakly dominated actions: In a strategic game with ordinal preferences, player $i$ ‚Äòs action $a_{i}^{\prime \prime}$ weakly dominates her action $a_{i}^{\prime}$ if</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>$u_{i}\left(a_{i}^{\prime \prime}, a_{-i}\right) \geq u_{i}\left(a_{i}^{\prime}, a_{-i}\right)$ for every list $a_{-i}$ of the other players‚Äô actions and</p>

<p>$u_{i}\left(a_{i}^{\prime \prime}, a_{-i}\right)&gt;u_{i}\left(a_{i}^{\prime}, a_{-i}\right)$ for some list $a_{-i}$ of the other players‚Äô actions, where $u_{i}$ is a payoff function that represents player i‚Äôs preferences. We say that the action $a_{i}^{\prime}$ is weakly dominated.</p>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Example: 10 is weakly dominated in the ‚Äúguess $\frac{2}{3}$ of the average‚Äù game.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Weakly dominated action may be used in a Nash equilibrium.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Examples: see next two figures. In both cases, $(C, C)$ is a Nash equilibrium in which both players‚Äô actions are weakly dominated. \begin{tabular}{c|c|c|} 
&amp; \multicolumn{1}{c}{$B$} &amp; \multicolumn{1}{c}{$C$} <br />
\hline $B$ &amp; 1,1 &amp; 2,0 <br />
\hline $C$ &amp; 0,2 &amp; 2,2 <br />
\hline  &amp; &amp;
\end{tabular}</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h3 id="example-voting">Example: voting</h3>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Two candidates, $A$ and $B$</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Odd number of voters</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Each prefers one candidate or the other</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Majority prefers candidate $A$</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Winner is candidate with most votes.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p><strong>Players:</strong> voters</p>

<p><strong>Actions:</strong> vote for $A$, vote for $B$. [No absention!]</p>

<p><strong>Preferences:</strong> each voter prefers outcome in which her favorite candidate wins to any outcome in which her favorite candidate loses.</p>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Some Nash equilibria [Exercise to find all]: all vote for $A$; all vote for $B$; each voter votes for more preferred candidate.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Each citizen‚Äôs strategy of voting for less preferred candidate is weakly dominated.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Suppose $i$ prefers $A$ to $B$. Fix others‚Äô votes.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>If $i$ switches from voting for $A$ to voting for $B$, either outcome doesn‚Äôt change or $B$ is elected rather than $A$, which is worse for $i$.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />
<h2 id="symmetric-games">Symmetric games</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Interaction between members of single population; steady state of single population.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>E.g. pedestrians approaching each other.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>A two-player strategic game with ordinal preferences is symmetric if the players‚Äô sets of actions are the same and the players‚Äô preferences are represented by payoff functions $u_{1}$ and $u_{2}$ for which $u_{1}\left(a_{1}, a_{2}\right)=$ $u_{2}\left(a_{2}, a_{1}\right)$ for every action pair $\left(a_{1}, a_{2}\right)$.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p><img src="https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/9f92a3071f00e68875165b31927b9e09-10.jpg?height=103&amp;width=833&amp;top_left_y=843&amp;top_left_x=217" alt="bg w:25cm" /></p>

<hr />

<p>Figure 6. The general form of a two-player symmetric game (left), and two examples, the Prisoner‚Äôs Dilemma (middle) and the two-player Stag Hunt (right).</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Symmetric equilibrium: An action profile $a^{<em>}$ in a strategic game with ordinal preferences in which each player has the same set of actions is a symmetric Nash equilibrium if it is a Nash equilibrium and $a_{i}^{</em>}$ is the same for every player $i$.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>E.g. non-symmetric equilibrium of approaching pedestrians game doesn‚Äôt make sense.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li>Symmetric game may not have symmetric equilibrium:</li>
</ul>

\[\def\arraystretch{1.5}
\begin{array}{|l|l|c|}
\hline &amp; L &amp; R\\
\hline U&amp;0,0 &amp; 1,1 \\
\hline D&amp; 1,1 &amp; 0,0 \\
\hline
\end{array}\]

<hr />

<p>Problems:</p>

<p>$37.1,38.1,38.2,42.1^{<em>}, 42.2^{</em>},\left(44.1^{<em>}\right), 47.1,47.2,48.1^{</em>},\left(49.1^{*}\right)$</p>

