<h2 id="experiment-guessing-two-thirds-of-the-average">Experiment: Guessing two-thirds of the average</h2>

<p>Note: this experiment corresponds to a single population steady state (for simplicity, because of symmetry of game).</p>

<p>Three players choose numbers. One with number closest to $\frac{2}{3}$ of the average wins.</p>

<p>Precisely:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Players: ${1,2,3}$</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Actions: ${1,2, \ldots, 10}$</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Payoffs: Let $g(a)=\frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{1}{3} \sum_{i=1}^{10} a_{i}\left(2 / 3\right.$ of average). If $\left</td>
          <td>a_{i}-g(a)\right</td>
          <td>&lt;$ $\left</td>
          <td>a_{j}-g(a)\right</td>
          <td>$ for all $j \neq i, i$ s payoff is $1 .$ Deal with ties $\ldots$</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p>[Note that unique equilibrium, $(1,1,1)$, is only strategy profile that survives successive elimination of weakly dominated strategies. If number of players is small (e.g. 3, as in exercise in book), smallest of three announced numbers is often the closest to $\frac{2}{3}$ of average, and thus wins. So players may deduce that they should play a small number, for not quite the right reason. To avoid this, could use more players (e.g. 5?).]</p>

<hr />

<p>Explain game. Give example: for $(3,2,8)$ the average is $\frac{13}{3}$, so $\frac{2}{3}$ of average is $2 \frac{8}{9}$. Thus winner is player 1 (who named 3). For $(3,1,5)$, average is 3 , so $\frac{2}{3}$ of average is 2, so players 1 and 2 are joint winners.</p>

<p>Pay $$ 5$ to the group with highest average payoff (total payoff divided by number of times the group played).</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Divide class into 10 groups - Give each group a set of 10 cards, numbered 1 to 10 (with group numbers in red)</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Load the APLII workspace guessavg and run the program play. (A file of the choices will be written to the file specified in the $\backslash x y \backslash m \backslash$ courses $\backslash 326$ directory.) The number of participants is the number of groups. The program is currently written for 3 players.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />
<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Or: in each round, generate a triple of numbers from 1 to 10 (the number of groups) randomly. These are the three groups who play in the round.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>The players in each round simultaneously show one of their cards.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Get an assistant to record the players in the round and their choices; the winning choice can be circled.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Repeat for several rounds.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>If get convergence to $(1,1,1):$ can see that $(1,1,1)$ is a Nash equilibrium. Why is no other action profile a Nash equilibrium?</p>

<hr />

<p>Discussion: Note that 1 is not the best action to use for every list of actions of the other players. E.g. if the others name 1 and 10, naming 1 yields $\frac{1}{2}$ whereas naming 2 yields $1 .$</p>

<p>Note that in the game actions can be iteratively eliminated.</p>

<p>What would happen if the game were to guess the average, rather than $2 / 3$ of the average? [Multiple equilibria-as Keynes suggested for the stock market.] (Exercise/exam question? Could play that game too.)</p>

